              "id": "QUE65287",
              "question": "How is inner-city poverty related to suburbanization in the United States?\n\u003cbr /\u003e",
              "order": "randomized",
              "presenterType": "RadioGroup",
              "presenterConfig": {
                "numberFormat": "none"
              },
              "choices": [
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_1",
                  "content": "With suburbanization, many U.S. cities lost higher-income taxpayers to the suburbs. Only the poor remained. Central cities fell into decline and poverty."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_2",
                  "content": "The same planners who designed suburbanization encouraged politicians to establish enterprise zones, which contributed to inner-city poverty."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_3",
                  "content": "Inner-city poverty led to the decline of cities. As cities fell into disrepair, new cities sprang up in less centralized locations. This is known as suburbanization."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_4",
                  "content": "Poverty increased in central cities in the 1950s. Cities began creating incentives for poor people to move elsewhere. These policies were the beginning of suburbanization."
                }
              ]
            },
